Testing #31831

Moving a line past a switch statement:
![movinglinethroughswitch](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9205389/28846831-c063158c-76c1-11e7-8f6c-ae9fb458845b.gif)

Text:
```js
var foo = 1 + 2;
switch (foobar) {
    case 1:
        var a = 2;
        break;
    case 2:
    default:
        var b = 4;
        break;
}
```

Testing #31831

Before:

```c
if (foo) {
  x = 1
}

if (bar) {
  y = 2;
}
```

Cut/paste the lower block below the `x = 1` line.

After:

```c
if (foo) {
  x = 1
  if (bar) {
  y = 2;
}
}
```

But if I move the `y = 2` line up and down, the indentation is correct

Testing #31831

I think it's fairly standard for preprocessor directives to be deindented

```c
int foo() {
    int x = 1;
#ifdef BAR
    return x;
#else
    return x+1;
#endif
}
```

But autoindent will put them at the same indentation level as the other code in the function body.
